annotations: ’Cause I’m a stalker, I seen all of your posts, ah-ah
I think you’re a stalker when you’ve seen all of their tagged photos. Right?

When a crush is truly intense, it can be hard to resist the temptation to go online and learn all you can about the other person, especially when social media makes it easier than ever. Is this why stalking is so often mischaracterized as sweet or romantic in Hollywood?

On Instagram, it’s commonly considered a faux pas to go through someone’s posts and hit “like” on all of them, not only because it shows the world that you looked at all those posts, but it also inundates your followers with outdated notifications. So when it’s difficult not to overthink, and you give in to the temptation of the social Internet, try to make your digital footprint as small as possible.
You think I’m tepid but I’m misdiagnosed

Tessa here is saying that her crush doesn’t realise how much she truly likes him. It’s implying that Tessa is subtly dropping hints in her interest, however he doesn’t seem to be getting the idea. Hence him “misdiagnosing” her.
[Bridge]

The whistle at the end of the bridge, I don’t know it just came to me. I liked the idea. I guess I’m always kind of rolling my eyes at myself, and the idea of the whistle feels very playful. And then because the bridge gets so kind of ramped up, the sigh is really is leaning into the craziness of it, and I like the idea of ending with something like that.
[Chorus]

The chorus melody came from my co-writers, Yacht Money, Lauren and Solomon Olds. They’re like, “What if we did something that kinda had this, kinda this hip hop feel to it?” And I was like, “Oo cool. Hip hop.” I’m a very pop background, and they have a more eclectic background I think. But I’m way into it, I love it.

You make it difficult to not overthink
 And when I’m with you I turn all shades of pink, ah

I’m struggling to be myself around you because I just want you to like me so much. And I think that’s maybe a little bit a sadder element of this is that it’s really longing for this desire to be wanted. I’d say the song internally comes from a place of deep loneliness, but then on the surface it’s trying to be like but we’re cool, we’re cool guys. Right? I don’t even wanna be with you. It’s just a crush.
’Cause I’m a stalker, I seen all of your posts, ah-ah
I think you’re a stalker when you’ve seen all of their tagged photos. Right?
I can’t focus on what needs to get done

That opening line, that was just my reality in that moment. I just felt like I have work that needs to be done, but I’m so just swimming in the feeling of let’s have a romance, and I’m so drawn to it, and I want it. And it’s so easy to write a song when you understand what you’re feeling. Or maybe you’re still working through what you’re feeling, which I sure was. So yeah that was my starting point.

description.plain:
“Yes Mom” is the title of Tessa Violet’s first solo single after her sophomore album, Bad Ideas. Originally played live on the “Something to Look Forward to Tour” on YouTube in 2020, the song was teased on December 19th, 2021, when Violet posted a TikTok with a produced clip of the song. In the beginning of the video, she puts up pictures of her from when she was a YouTuber under the name “Meekakitty”, transitioning to a clip of her now.

On January 7th, 2022, Violet released the pre-save link for the song, and, after reaching 20,000 pre-saves on January 12th, she released a TikTok with the first verse of the song.

On February 7th, Violet tweeted about the song “Yesterday” by The Beatles, starting a 26-tweet long series. Reading the first letter of each tweet says “yes mom comes out tuesday night”. She then changed her bio on Twitter to “11:18 2/7/22”, referring back to the tweet that started the series, and also changed her profile pictures on Twitter, TikTok, and Instagram to solid black. Over the following three days, she progressively revealed the cover art of the song in 9 separate pieces, uploading one at a time as her profile picture, before the song was officially released on February 16th, 2022.

annotations:
Bet you’ve been a fan of me
 See me in your fantasies

According to Tessa Violet in an interview with Genius, the chorus was initially written differently to convey Tessa’s desire of being bold, confident, and all-in-all loving for who she is. While Tessa retained her original approach, she took a step back and considered her listeners' perspective, as some listeners might not agree with Tessa’s standards of self-love due to low self-esteem issues. Consequently, Tessa changed the concept to “bad bitch energy”:

I love everything I am (Yes Mom)
Perfect just the way I am (Yes Mom)
Rising like a phoenix making fire from the ash, yeah

Phoenixes are mythical creatures that burst into flames upon their death and are reborn from the ashes. Tessa is using this lore as a metaphor for strength and overcoming a hard past, as mentioned in the previous line.
Did it independent ’cause I got what I need so

In this lyric, Violet is likely referring to the fact that she is an independent artist who has been able to succeed thanks to her talents. Independent artists are those who are not signed under a record label.

description.plain: Smoke Signals was written by Robin Skinner (Cavetown) and Tessa Violet. It was publicized on July 10, 2020, with the cover image of a light blue house in a metropolitan area. It was described by a user on Youtube as “the ultimate 2 am-sitting-in-bed-overthinking songwriter" type of song. The lyrics gently relate to the difficulties of a relationship, especially one in which a romantic partner is still looking for signs from their significant other, because they still care despite any unrest.

annotations:
I left the gate unlocked for you
 Till then I’m sending out smoke signals
 Hoping I’ll see yours too

Smoke signals are something you see but they can also represent maybe like vapor or evaporating to something.  Considering someone left (Verse 1)  It can represent how they have basically disintegrated to and into thin air.

If you’re feeling spent
 When it’s heavy on your chest
 When you think there’s nothing left

I think this line could be representing something similar to the chorus, because it says that the person who the main character is not seeing can go talk to them whenever they need to, with the difference that in the chorus they tell them that they can come back to them when “they are ready” and in this verse, when “it’s heavy” on the other’s person chest. In both cases the main character wants the person to come back.
When the dust has set
A metaphor referring to the aftermath of a storm or big disturbance, in which the dust settles in the ensuing calm that occurs once the event has taken place.

I left the gate unlocked for you
 Till then I’m sending out smoke signals
 Hoping I’ll see yours too

Leaving the gate unlocked is referring to the way in which this person still cares about whoever has gone away, and so they have kept the path back to them “unlocked” and available for their return.
     Sending out smoke signals is a great way to describe the way communication becomes almost code-like and distant in a relationship when there has been a disruption between the two participants. Smoke signals arise from campfires, which could be alluding to their burning affection or hearts in this case, as well. Thus, these signals could represent attempts between partners, despite the distance they have created between themselves, to find each other again.

I hope you found a place to sleep
 I know you’re bound to think of me

These lyrics are describing the sentiments of a romantic or caring partner that ultimately still loves whoever they are thinking about, and so they are wishing them well and recognizing that there is still some sort of connection between them.

Ripped the Band-Aid, broke the peace
 Took the lock but lost the key
 Guess I set you free

These lyrics could relate to how someone in a romantic relationship finally addresses an issue and, in doing so, “rips the Band-Aid” off and “breaks the peace”. Ripping a Band-Aid off is never a pleasant experience, and if it’s done too early, it can disrupt the healing process of a wound.
Taking the lock and losing the key could be referring to how it was a useless plan in the first place, because in doing so, there is no use for the “lock”, or the argument, anymore, because the “key”, or the relevance, is gone.
     Behaving this way has hurt the relationship, and this person is reflecting on the idea that maybe their mistake has finally “freed” their partner from their own “freak”-ish nature.

annotations:
[Chorus]
 Oh, wishful drinkin’
 Tell myself that I’m not thinkin’ ’bout
 How I could drown, drown, drown, drown
 Wishful drinkin’, oh

“Wishful Drinking” is a pun on the term “wishful thinking”, which describes reasoning that is unrealistically optimistic.  From the lyrics, we can infer that the narrator has already begun to engage in unhealthy drinking habits, but repeatedly denies that it has become a problem.  In this line, she is even denying it to herself, while “wishing” that the problem doesn’t become worse.

This is not a problem if I don’t want it to stop
 Can’t call it a problem if I never let a plate drop
 This is not a problem if convincin’ that it’s not (Oh)
 Don’t call it a problem, it’s the only thing that I still got
The narrator is (presumably) upset that others think it is a problem that they are “drowning” their emotions and thinks it isn’t a problem because they don’t want to try to stop themselves.

description.plain:
“Bad Ideas” is the third song on Tessa Violet’s second album with the same name. Tessa released a teaser for the song’s music video on YouTube on the 25th of November 2018. The actual music video was released on the 1st of December 2018.



The song tells of Tessa’s longing to be with someone even as she knows the relationship will end badly. It is a bad idea to even try, yet she does anyway, too obsessed with the feeling of infatuation. The theme is quite similar to her first single from the album, “Crush,” which also comes right before “Bad Ideas” in the tracklist. However, this song’s underlying bittersweet message is clearer than that of “Crush.”

But I want to make out with you
 And I’m a little awkward, sure
 But I could touch my face to yours, oh

In an interview with Dailycal, Tessa explained how  these “unapologetically awkward” lyrics came to be a part of her song.

A lot of things that I just say in life, things I say to other people, end up within my songs.
To do the very thing that fells me

In the music video of “Bad Ideas”, right as this line is sung, Violet cuts a piece of her hair. Cutting one’s hair is almost universally considered a bad idea, which lends itself very well to the title of Violet’s song.



This is also where the album artwork (several hands with scissors around Violet’s hair) comes from.
It takes everything I got not to text

This lyric serves as a callback to Violet’s first single from Bad Ideas, “Crush”:

Hoping you’d text me so I could tell you I been thinking ‘bout your touch like

It may also reference her earlier song “Not over You”:

But I gotta know how you can tweet but you can’t text me

However, in this case, Violet turns the attention onto herself instead of her crush. Instead of wishing her crush would text her, she tries to restrain herself from texting them.
I wanna kiss you standing up

Tessa explained this line in a Patreon livestream on November 29, 2018. Since she is such a tall person (5'9") she is typically not shorter than love interests, but this particular crush was taller than her. Kissing a taller guy made her feel more cute and feminine, since girls are stereotyped as shorter and smaller. She wants this fairytale type of romance even if it won’t last.

description.plain:
Tessa Violet wrote “I Like (the idea of) You” as a flip of her old song “Bad Ideas,” using the same story but from a different perspective. She tells MTV:

I was seeing this guy at the time who I knew wasn’t that into me. And even though I could see that, it was still so much fun to think and obsess about him. I remember that I could logically see it wasn’t going anywhere, so I thought maybe I should feel embarrassed about how much time I was spending on him. But it didn’t make me feel embarrassed, it made me feel sexy and powerful. So what if they’re not that into me? I like the idea of it and I’m going to enjoy that.

The song debuted live before being officially released as a single on May 3rd, 2019.

annotations:
But I like the idea-dea of you
 I like the idea-dea of you
 Wonder how it’d be, be to love you
 I like the idea-dea of you, ooh

sometimes the fantasy of someone and what could be, is more fun, and more important than the reality. sometimes having someone who is enough is all you need, because you can project fantasies onto them, but not be disappointed when they fail to meet them, when you’ve already acknowledged that they’re basically just a stand-in for the dream.
I keep repeating, repeating the way you say my name

Even though Tessa acknowledges that her crush isn’t going anywhere, she still enjoys thinking about it. She mentioned the inspiration behind this line in an interview with MTV:

[I would keep] replaying the way he said my name on the phone, imagining what I would wear or say the next time I saw him, thinking of things I could write about him.

description.plain:
“Games” details a toxic relationship which Tessa’s partner tried to assure her was normal. In the song Tessa stands up for herself and breaks away from the relationship.

The artist played this song for the first time during an Instagram live stream in October 2018, though she changed the chorus and bridge since then. On September 22nd, 2019, Tessa shared a teaser of the song, adding that it would be released five days later. The song is part of her debut studio album, Bad Ideas.
